[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm finds the shortest path from a given source node to every other node.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be used to find the shortest path to a specific destination node, by terminating the algorithm after determining the shortest path to that node.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the nodes of the graph represent cities, and the costs of edges represent the distances between pairs of cities connected by a direct road, then Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to find the shortest route between one city and all other cities.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A common application of shortest path algorithms is network routing protocols, most notably IS-IS (Intermediate System to Intermediate System) and OSPF (Open Shortest Path First).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It is also employed as a subroutine in algorithms such as Johnson's algorithm.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm uses a min-priority queue data structure for selecting the shortest paths known so far.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Before more advanced priority queue structures were discovered, Dijkstra's original algorithm ran in $\Theta (|V|^{2})$ time, where $|V|$ is the number of nodes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Fredman & Tarjan 1984 proposed a Fibonacci heap priority queue to optimize the running time complexity to $\Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ , where $|E|$ is the number of edges.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is asymptotically the fastest known single-source shortest-path algorithm for arbitrary directed graphs with unbounded non-negative weights.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, specialized cases (such as bounded/integer weights, directed acyclic graphs etc.) can be improved further.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If preprocessing is allowed, algorithms such as contraction hierarchies can be up to seven orders of magnitude faster.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is commonly used on graphs where the edge weights are positive integers or real numbers.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be generalized to any graph where the edge weights are partially ordered, provided the subsequent labels (a subsequent label is produced when traversing an edge) are monotonically non-decreasing.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In many fields, particularly artificial intelligence, Dijkstra's algorithm or a variant offers a uniform cost search and is formulated as an instance of the more general idea of best-first search.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] — Edsger Dijkstra, in an interview with Philip L.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra thought about the shortest path problem while working as a programmer at the Mathematical Center in Amsterdam in 1956.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He wanted to demonstrate the capabilities of the new ARMAC computer.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] His objective was to choose a problem and a computer solution that non-computing people could understand.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He designed the shortest path algorithm and later implemented it for ARMAC for a slightly simplified transportation map of 64 cities in the Netherlands (he limited it to 64, so that 6 bits would be sufficient to encode the city number).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A year later, he came across another problem advanced by hardware engineers working on the institute's next computer: minimize the amount of wire needed to connect the pins on the machine's back panel.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As a solution, he re-discovered Prim's minimal spanning tree algorithm (known earlier to Jarník, and also rediscovered by Prim).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra published the algorithm in 1959, two years after Prim and 29 years after Jarník.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm requires a starting node, and computes the shortest distance from that starting node to each other node.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assign to every node a distance from start value: for the starting node, it is zero, and for all other nodes, it is infinity, since initially no path is known to these nodes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] During execution, the distance of a node *N* is the length of the shortest path discovered so far between the starting node and *N*.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the unvisited set, select the current node to be the one with the smallest (finite) distance; initially, this is the starting node (distance zero).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the unvisited set is empty, or contains only nodes with infinite distance (which are unreachable), then the algorithm terminates by skipping to step 6.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the only concern is the path to a target node, the algorithm terminates once the current node is the target node.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the current node, consider all of its unvisited neighbors and update their distances through the current node; compare the newly calculated distance to the one currently assigned to the neighbor and assign the smaller one to it.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the current node *A* is marked with a distance of 6, and the edge connecting it with its neighbor *B* has length 2, then the distance to *B* through *A* is 6 + 2 = 8.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If B was previously marked with a distance greater than 8, then update it to 8 (the path to B through A is shorter).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Otherwise, keep its current distance (the path to B through A is not the shortest).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After considering all of the current node's unvisited neighbors, the current node is removed from the unvisited set.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Thus a visited node is never rechecked, which is correct because the distance recorded on the current node is minimal (as ensured in step 3), and thus final.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once the loop exits (steps 3–5), every visited node contains its shortest distance from the starting node.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The shortest path between two intersections on a city map can be found by this algorithm using pencil and paper.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every intersection is listed on a separate line: one is the starting point and is labeled (given a distance of) 0.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every other intersection is initially labeled with a distance of infinity.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is done to note that no path to these intersections has yet been established.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At each iteration one intersection becomes the current intersection.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the first iteration, this is the starting point.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the current intersection, the distance to every neighbor (directly-connected) intersection is assessed by summing the label (value) of the current intersection and the distance to the neighbor and then relabeling the neighbor with the lesser of that sum and the neighbor's existing label.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] I.e., the neighbor is relabeled if the path to it through the current intersection is shorter than previously assessed paths.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If so, mark the road to the neighbor with an arrow pointing to it, and erase any other arrow that points to it.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After the distances to each of the current intersection's neighbors have been assessed, the current intersection is marked as visited.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The unvisited intersection with the smallest label becomes the current intersection and the process repeats until all nodes with labels less than the destination's label have been visited.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once no unvisited nodes remain with a label smaller than the destination's label, the remaining arrows show the shortest path.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following pseudocode, dist is an array that contains the current distances from the *source* to other vertices, i.e. dist[*u*] is the current distance from the source to the vertex *u*.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The prev array contains pointers to previous-hop nodes on the shortest path from source to the given vertex (equivalently, it is the *next-hop* on the path *from* the given vertex *to* the source).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The code u ← vertex in *Q* with min dist[u], searches for the vertex *u* in the vertex set *Q* that has the least dist[*u*] value.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph.Distance(*u*,*v*) returns the length of the edge joining (i.e. the distance between) the two neighbor-nodes *u* and *v*.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The variable *alt* on line 14 is the length of the path from the *source* node to the neighbor node *v* if it were to go through *u*.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If this path is shorter than the current shortest path recorded for *v*, then the distance of *v* is updated to *alt*.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To find the shortest path between vertices *source* and *target*, the search terminates after line 10 if *u* = *target*.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Now sequence *S* is the list of vertices constituting one of the shortest paths from *source* to *target*, or the empty sequence if no path exists.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A more general problem is to find all the shortest paths between *source* and *target* (there might be several of the same length).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then instead of storing only a single node in each entry of prev[] all nodes satisfying the relaxation condition can be stored.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if both *r* and *source* connect to *target* and they lie on different shortest paths through *target* (because the edge cost is the same in both cases), then both *r* and *source* are added to prev[*target*].
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When the algorithm completes, prev[] data structure describes a graph that is a subset of the original graph with some edges removed.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Its key property is that if the algorithm was run with some starting node, then every path from that node to any other node in the new graph is the shortest path between those nodes graph, and all paths of that length from the original graph are present in the new graph.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then to actually find all these shortest paths between two given nodes, a path finding algorithm on the new graph, such as depth-first search would work.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A min-priority queue is an abstract data type that provides 3 basic operations: add_with_priority(), decrease_priority() and extract_min().
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As mentioned earlier, using such a data structure can lead to faster computing times than using a basic queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Notably, Fibonacci heap or Brodal queue offer optimal implementations for those 3 operations.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Instead of filling the priority queue with all nodes in the initialization phase, it is possible to initialize it to contain only *source*; then, inside the `**if** *alt* < dist[*v*]` block, the decrease_priority() becomes an add_with_priority() operation.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Yet another alternative is to add nodes unconditionally to the priority queue and to instead check after extraction (`*u* ← *Q*.extract_min()`) that it isn't revisiting, or that no shorter connection was found yet in the `if alt < dist[v]` block.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This can be done by additionally extracting the associated priority `*p*` from the queue and only processing further `**if** *p* == dist[*u*]` inside the `**while** *Q* is not empty` loop.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] These alternatives can use entirely array-based priority queues without decrease-key functionality, which have been found to achieve even faster computing times in practice.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, the difference in performance was found to be narrower for denser graphs.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To prove the correctness of Dijkstra's algorithm, mathematical induction can be used on the number of visited nodes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The base case is when there is just one visited node, source.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Its distance is defined to be zero, which is the shortest distance, since negative weights are not allowed.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assuming that the hypothesis holds for k visited nodes, to show it holds for $k+1$ nodes, let u be the next visited node, i.e. the node with minimum `dist[u]`.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The claim is that `dist[u]` is the shortest distance from source to u.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If a shorter path were available, then this shorter path either contains another unvisited node or not.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For all other visited nodes v, the `dist[v]` is already known to be the shortest distance from source, because of the inductive hypothesis, and these values are unchanged.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After processing u, it is still true that for each unvisited node w, `dist[w]` is the shortest distance from source to w using visited nodes only.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Any shorter path that did not use u, would already have been found, and if a shorter path used u it would have been updated when processing u.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After all nodes are visited, the shortest path from source to any node v consists only of visited nodes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Therefore, `dist[v]` is the shortest distance.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Bounds of the running time of Dijkstra's algorithm on a graph with edges E and vertices V can be expressed as a function of the number of edges, denoted $|E|$ , and the number of vertices, denoted $|V|$ , using big-O notation.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The complexity bound depends mainly on the data structure used to represent the set Q.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following, upper bounds can be simplified because $|E|$ is $O(|V|^{2})$ for any simple graph, but that simplification disregards the fact that in some problems, other upper bounds on $|E|$ may hold.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] where $T_{\mathrm {dk} }$ and $T_{\mathrm {em} }$ are the complexities of the *decrease-key* and *extract-minimum* operations in Q, respectively.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The simplest version of Dijkstra's algorithm stores the vertex set Q as a linked list or array, and edges as an adjacency list or matrix.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In this case, extract-minimum is simply a linear search through all vertices in Q, so the running time is ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|+|V|^{2})=\Theta (|V|^{2})}$ .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To perform decrease-key steps in a binary heap efficiently, it is necessary to use an auxiliary data structure that maps each vertex to its position in the heap, and to update this structure as the priority queue Q changes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] With a self-balancing binary search tree or binary heap, the algorithm requires ${\textstyle \Theta ((|E|+|V|)\log |V|)}$ time in the worst case; for connected graphs this time bound can be simplified to ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|\log |V|)}$ .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The Fibonacci heap improves this to ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)}$ .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In common presentations of Dijkstra's algorithm, initially all nodes are entered into the priority queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is, however, not necessary: the algorithm can start with a priority queue that contains only one item, and insert new items as they are discovered (instead of doing a decrease-key, check whether the key is in the queue; if it is, decrease its key, otherwise insert it).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This variant has the same worst-case bounds as the common variant, but maintains a smaller priority queue in practice, speeding up queue operations.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Moreover, not inserting all nodes in a graph makes it possible to extend the algorithm to find the shortest path from a single source to the closest of a set of target nodes on infinite graphs or those too large to represent in memory.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Combinations of such techniques may be needed for optimal practical performance on specific problems.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Two distance arrays are maintained: *df*[*v*] (distance from s to v) and *db*[*v*] (distance from v to t), initialized to ∞ except *df*[*s*] = 0 and *db*[*t*] = 0.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Two priority queues *Qf* and *Qb* hold vertices not yet fully processed, and two sets *Sf* and *Sb* store vertices whose shortest-path distance is finalized in each direction.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A variable μ stores the length of the best full s–t path found so far, initially ∞.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] and symmetrically for the backward search.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A key feature is the stopping condition: once the sum of the current minimum priorities in both queues is at least μ, no yet-unsettled path can improve upon μ.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At this point μ equals the true shortest-path distance δ(*s*,*t*), and the search terminates.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This criterion avoids a common mistake of halting as soon as the two frontiers touch, which may overlook a shorter alternative crossing elsewhere.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because each search only needs to explore roughly half of the search space in typical graphs, the bidirectional method often visits far fewer vertices and relaxes far fewer edges than one-directional Dijkstra on single-pair queries.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In road-network–like graphs the savings can be dramatic, sometimes reducing the explored region from an exponential-size ball to two smaller half-balls.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The method is widely used in point-to-point routing for maps and navigation software and serves as a base for many speed-up techniques such as the ALT, contraction hierarchies, and reach-based routing.
