[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of these considerations, most real-world systems use specialized Dijkstra variants tuned for specific graph families and hardware constraints.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As well as simply computing distances and paths, Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to sort vertices by their distances from a given starting vertex.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To achieve this, they use a comparison-based heap whose cost of returning/removing the minimum element from the heap is logarithmic in the number of elements inserted after it rather than in the number of elements in the heap.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When arc weights are small integers (bounded by a parameter C ), specialized queues can be used for increased speed.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The first algorithm of this type was Dial's algorithm for graphs with positive integer edge weights, which uses a bucket queue to obtain a running time $O(|E|+|V|C)$ .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The use of a Van Emde Boas tree as the priority queue brings the complexity to $O(|E|+|V|\log C/\log \log |V|C)$ .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Another interesting variant based on a combination of a new radix heap and the well-known Fibonacci heap runs in time $O(|E|+|V|{\sqrt {\log C}})$ .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's original algorithm can be extended with modifications.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, sometimes it is desirable to present solutions which are less than mathematically optimal.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To obtain a ranked list of less-than-optimal solutions, the optimal solution is first calculated.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A single edge appearing in the optimal solution is removed from the graph, and the optimum solution to this new graph is calculated.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Each edge of the original solution is suppressed in turn and a new shortest-path calculated.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The secondary solutions are then ranked and presented after the first optimal solution.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is usually the working principle behind link-state routing protocols.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Unlike Dijkstra's algorithm, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can be used on graphs with negative edge weights, as long as the graph contains no negative cycle reachable from the source vertex *s*.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The presence of such cycles means that no shortest path can be found, since the label becomes lower each time the cycle is traversed.
