[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The A* algorithm is a generalization of Dijkstra's algorithm that reduces the size of the subgraph that must be explored, if additional information is available that provides a lower bound on the distance to the target.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The process that underlies Dijkstra's algorithm is similar to the greedy process used in Prim's algorithm.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Prim's purpose is to find a minimum spanning tree that connects all nodes in the graph; Dijkstra is concerned with only two nodes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Prim's does not evaluate the total weight of the path from the starting node, only the individual edges.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Breadth-first search can be viewed as a special-case of Dijkstra's algorithm on unweighted graphs, where the priority queue degenerates into a FIFO queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The fast marching method can be viewed as a continuous version of Dijkstra's algorithm which computes the geodesic distance on a triangle mesh.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From a dynamic programming point of view, Dijkstra's algorithm is a successive approximation scheme that solves the dynamic programming functional equation for the shortest path problem by the **Reaching** method.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/dijkstra-s-algorithm] is a paraphrasing of Bellman's principle of optimality in the context of the shortest path problem.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] In computer science, **graph traversal** (also known as **graph search**) refers to the process of visiting (checking and/or updating) each vertex in a graph.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] Such traversals are classified by the order in which the vertices are visited.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] Tree traversal is a special case of graph traversal.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] Unlike tree traversal, graph traversal may require that some vertices be visited more than once, since it is not necessarily known before transitioning to a vertex that it has already been explored.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] As graphs become more dense, this redundancy becomes more prevalent, causing computation time to increase; as graphs become more sparse, the opposite holds true.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] Thus, it is usually necessary to remember which vertices have already been explored by the algorithm, so that vertices are revisited as infrequently as possible (or in the worst case, to prevent the traversal from continuing indefinitely).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] This may be accomplished by associating each vertex of the graph with a "color" or "visitation" state during the traversal, which is then checked and updated as the algorithm visits each vertex.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] If the vertex has already been visited, it is ignored and the path is pursued no further; otherwise, the algorithm checks/updates the vertex and continues down its current path.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] Several special cases of graphs imply the visitation of other vertices in their structure, and thus do not require that visitation be explicitly recorded during the traversal.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] An important example of this is a tree: during a traversal it may be assumed that all "ancestor" vertices of the current vertex (and others depending on the algorithm) have already been visited.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] Both the depth-first and breadth-first graph searches are adaptations of tree-based algorithms, distinguished primarily by the lack of a structurally determined "root" vertex and the addition of a data structure to record the traversal's visitation state.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] Note. — If each vertex in a graph is to be traversed by a tree-based algorithm (such as DFS or BFS), then the algorithm must be called at least once for each connected component of the graph.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] This is easily accomplished by iterating through all the vertices of the graph, performing the algorithm on each vertex that is still unvisited when examined.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] A depth-first search (DFS) is an algorithm for traversing a finite graph.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] DFS visits the child vertices before visiting the sibling vertices; that is, it traverses the depth of any particular path before exploring its breadth.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] A stack (often the program's call stack via recursion) is generally used when implementing the algorithm.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] The algorithm begins with a chosen "root" vertex; it then iteratively transitions from the current vertex to an adjacent, unvisited vertex, until it can no longer find an unexplored vertex to transition to from its current location.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] The algorithm then backtracks along previously visited vertices, until it finds a vertex connected to yet more uncharted territory.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] It will then proceed down the new path as it had before, backtracking as it encounters dead-ends, and ending only when the algorithm has backtracked past the original "root" vertex from the very first step.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] DFS is the basis for many graph-related algorithms, including topological sorts and planarity testing.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] A breadth-first search (BFS) is another technique for traversing a finite graph.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] BFS visits the sibling vertices before visiting the child vertices, and a queue is used in the search process.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] This algorithm is often used to find the shortest path from one vertex to another.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] The problem of graph exploration can be seen as a variant of graph traversal.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] It is an online problem, meaning that the information about the graph is only revealed during the runtime of the algorithm.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] A common model is as follows: given a connected graph *G* = (*V*, *E*) with non-negative edge weights.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] The algorithm starts at some vertex, and knows all incident outgoing edges and the vertices at the end of these edges—but not more.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] When a new vertex is visited, then again all incident outgoing edges and the vertices at the end are known.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] The goal is to visit all *n* vertices and return to the starting vertex, but the sum of the weights of the tour should be as small as possible.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] The problem can also be understood as a specific version of the travelling salesman problem, where the salesman has to discover the graph on the go.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] A *universal traversal sequence* is a sequence of instructions comprising a graph traversal for any regular graph with a set number of vertices and for any starting vertex.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] A probabilistic proof was used by Aleliunas et al. to show that there exists a universal traversal sequence with number of instructions proportional to *O*(*n*5) for any regular graph with *n* vertices.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] The steps specified in the sequence are relative to the current node, not absolute.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/graph-traversal] For example, if the current node is *v**j*, and *v**j* has *d* neighbors, then the traversal sequence will specify the next node to visit, *v**j*+1, as the *i*th neighbor of *v**j*, where 1 ≤ *i* ≤ *d*.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] The ***k* shortest path routing** problem is a generalization of the shortest path routing problem in a given network.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] It asks not only about a shortest path but also about next *k−1* shortest paths (which may be longer than the shortest path).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] A variation of the problem is the loopless *k* shortest paths.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Finding *k* shortest paths is possible by extending Dijkstra's algorithm or the Bellman-Ford algorithm.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Since 1957, many papers have been published on the *k* shortest path routing problem.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Most of the fundamental works were done between 1960s and 2001.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Since then, most of the research has been on the problem's applications and its variants.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] In 2010, Michael Günther et al. published a book on *Symbolic calculation of*k*-shortest paths and related measures with the stochastic process algebra tool CASPA*.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Dijkstra's algorithm can be generalized to find the *k* shortest paths.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] There are two main variations of the *k* shortest path routing problem.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] In one variation, paths are allowed to visit the same node more than once, thus creating loops.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] In another variation, paths are required to be simple and loopless.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] The loopy version is solvable using Eppstein's algorithm and the loopless variation is solvable by Yen's algorithm.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] In this variant, the problem is simplified by not requiring paths to be loopless.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Fox in 1975 in which the *k*-shortest paths are determined in *O*(*m* + *kn* log *n*) asymptotic time complexity (using big *O* notation).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] In 1998, David Eppstein reported an approach that maintains an asymptotic complexity of *O*(*m* + *n* log *n* + *k*) by computing an implicit representation of the paths, each of which can be output in *O*(*n*) extra time.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] In 2015, Akiba *et al.* devised an indexing method as a significantly faster alternative for Eppstein's algorithm, in which a data structure called an index is constructed from a graph and then top-*k* distances between arbitrary pairs of vertices can be rapidly obtained.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] In the loopless variant, the paths are forbidden to contain loops, which adds an additional level of complexity.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] It can be solved using Yen's algorithm to find the lengths of all shortest paths from a fixed node to all other nodes in an *n*-node non negative-distance network, a technique requiring only 2*n*2 additions and *n*2 comparison, fewer than other available shortest path algorithms need.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] The running time complexity is pseudo-polynomial, being *O*(*kn*(*m* + *n* log *n*)) (where *m* and *n* represent the number of edges and vertices, respectively).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] In 2007, John Hershberger and Subhash Suri proposed a replacement paths algorithm, a more efficient implementation of Lawler's and Yen's algorithm with *O*(*n*) improvement in time for a large number of graphs, but not all of them (therefore not changing the asymptotic bound of Yen's algorithm).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] The following example makes use of Yen's model to find *k* shortest paths between communicating end nodes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] That is, it finds a shortest path, second shortest path, etc. up to the Kth shortest path.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Another example is the use of *k* shortest paths algorithm to track multiple objects.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] The technique implements a multiple object tracker based on the *k* shortest paths routing algorithm.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] A set of probabilistic occupancy maps is used as input.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] The complete details can be found at "Computer Vision Laboratory – CVLAB".
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Another use of *k* shortest paths algorithms is to design a transit network that enhances passengers' experience in public transportation systems.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Such an example of a transit network can be constructed by putting traveling time under consideration.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] In addition to traveling time, other conditions may be taken depending upon economical and geographical limitations.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Despite variations in parameters, the *k* shortest path algorithms finds the most optimal solutions that satisfies almost all user needs.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Such applications of *k* shortest path algorithms are becoming common, recently Xu, He, Song, and Chaudhry (2012) studied the *k* shortest path problems in transit network systems.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/k-shortest-path-routing] Cherkassky et al. provide more algorithms and associated evaluations.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In computer science, a **priority queue** is an abstract data type similar to a regular queue where each element has an associated priority determining its order of service.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Priority queue serves highest priority items first.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Priority values have to be instances of an ordered data type, and higher priority can be given either to the lesser or to the greater values with respect to the given order relation.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For example, in the Java standard library, the PriorityQueue class considers the lowest element with respect to their order as having the highest priority.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] While priority queues are often implemented using heaps, they are conceptually distinct.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] A priority queue can be implemented with a heap or with other methods; just as a list can be implemented with a linked list or with an array.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Stacks and queues can be implemented as particular kinds of priority queues, with the priority determined by the order in which the elements are inserted.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In a stack, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically increasing; thus, the last element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In a queue, the priority of each inserted element is monotonically decreasing; thus, the first element inserted is always the first retrieved.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In some implementations, if two elements have the same priority, they are served in the same order in which they were enqueued.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In other implementations, the order of elements with the same priority is undefined.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] One can create a simple, but inefficient priority queue in a number of ways.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] These naive implementations can demonstrate the expected behaviour of a priority queue in a simpler manner.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] To improve performance, priority queues are typically based on a heap, giving $O(\log n)$ performance for inserts and removals, and $O(n)$ to build the heap initially from a set of n elements.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Variants of the basic heap data structure such as pairing heaps or Fibonacci heaps can provide better bounds for some operations.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] From a space-complexity standpoint, using self-balancing binary search tree with linked list takes more storage, since it requires storing extra references to other nodes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] From a computational-complexity standpoint, priority queues are congruent to sorting algorithms.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The section on the equivalence of priority queues and sorting algorithms, below, describes how efficient sorting algorithms can create efficient priority queues.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] There are several specialized heap data structures that either supply additional operations or outperform heap-based implementations for specific types of keys, specifically integer keys.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For applications that do many "peek" operations for every "`extract-min`" operation, the time complexity for peek actions can be reduced to $O(1)$ in all tree and heap implementations by caching the highest priority element after every insertion and removal.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For insertion, this adds at most a constant cost, since the newly inserted element is compared only to the previously cached minimum element.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For deletion, this at most adds an additional "peek" cost, which is typically cheaper than the deletion cost, so overall time complexity is not significantly impacted.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Monotone priority queues are specialized queues that are optimized for the case where no item is ever inserted that has a lower priority (in the case of min-heap) than any item previously extracted.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] This restriction is met by several practical applications of priority queues.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Here are time complexities of various heap data structures.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The abbreviation am. indicates that the given complexity is amortized, otherwise it is a worst-case complexity.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For the meaning of "*O*(*f*)" and "*Θ*(*f*)" see Big O notation.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For persistent heaps (not supporting *decrease-key*), a generic transformation reduces the cost of *meld* to that of *insert*, while the new cost of *delete-min* is the sum of the old costs of *delete-min* and *meld*.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Here, it makes *meld* run in *Θ*(1) time (amortized, if the cost of *insert* is) while *delete-min* still runs in *O*(log *n*).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Applied to skew binomial heaps, it yields Brodal-Okasaki queues, persistent heaps with optimal worst-case complexities.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Brodal queues and strict Fibonacci heaps achieve optimal worst-case complexities for heaps.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] They were first described as imperative data structures.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The Brodal-Okasaki queue is a persistent data structure achieving the same optimum, except that *decrease-key* is not supported.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The semantics of priority queues naturally suggest a sorting method: insert all the elements to be sorted into a priority queue, and sequentially remove them; they will come out in sorted order.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] This is actually the procedure used by several sorting algorithms, once the layer of abstraction provided by the priority queue is removed.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] A sorting algorithm can also be used to implement a priority queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For example, if one has an $O(n\log n)$ sort algorithm, one can create a priority queue with $O(1)$ pulling and $O(\log n)$ insertion.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] A priority queue is often considered to be a "container data structure".
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The Standard Template Library (STL), and the C++ 1998 standard, specifies std::priority_queue as one of the STL container adaptor class templates.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] However, it does not specify how two elements with same priority should be served, and indeed, common implementations will not return them according to their order in the queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Unlike actual STL containers, it does not allow iteration of its elements (it strictly adheres to its abstract data type definition).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] STL also has utility functions for manipulating another random-access container as a binary max-heap.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The Boost libraries also have an implementation in the library heap.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Python's heapq module implements a binary min-heap on top of a list.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Java's library contains a `PriorityQueue` (`java.util.PriorityQueue`) class, which implements a min-priority-queue as a binary heap.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] .NET's library contains a System.Collections.Generic.PriorityQueue class, which implements an array-backed, quaternary min-heap.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Scala's library contains a scala.collection.mutable.PriorityQueue class, which implements a max-priority-queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Go's library contains a container/heap module, which implements a min-heap on top of any compatible data structure.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Rust's standard library contains a std::collections::BinaryHeap struct, which implements a priority queue with a binary heap.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The Standard PHP Library extension contains the class SplPriorityQueue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Apple's Core Foundation framework contains a CFBinaryHeap structure, which implements a min-heap.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Priority queuing can be used to manage limited resources such as bandwidth on a transmission line from a network router.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In the event of outgoing traffic queuing due to insufficient bandwidth, all other queues can be halted to send the traffic from the highest priority queue upon arrival.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] This ensures that the prioritized traffic (such as real-time traffic, e.g. an RTP stream of a VoIP connection) is forwarded with the least delay and the least likelihood of being rejected due to a queue reaching its maximum capacity.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] All other traffic can be handled when the highest priority queue is empty.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Another approach used is to send disproportionately more traffic from higher priority queues.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Many modern protocols for local area networks also include the concept of priority queues at the media access control (MAC) sub-layer to ensure that high-priority applications (such as VoIP or IPTV) experience lower latency than other applications which can be served with best-effort service.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Examples include IEEE 802.11e (an amendment to IEEE 802.11 which provides quality of service) and ITU-T G.hn (a standard for high-speed local area network using existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Usually a limitation (policer) is set to limit the bandwidth that traffic from the highest priority queue can take, in order to prevent high priority packets from choking off all other traffic.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] This limit is usually never reached due to high level control instances such as the Cisco Callmanager, which can be programmed to inhibit calls which would exceed the programmed bandwidth limit.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Another use of a priority queue is to manage the events in a discrete event simulation.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The events are added to the queue with their simulation time used as the priority.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The execution of the simulation proceeds by repeatedly pulling the top of the queue and executing the event thereon.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] When the graph is stored in the form of adjacency list or matrix, priority queue can be used to extract minimum efficiently when implementing Dijkstra's algorithm, although one also needs the ability to alter the priority of a particular vertex in the priority queue efficiently.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] If instead, a graph is stored as node objects, and priority-node pairs are inserted into a heap, altering the priority of a particular vertex is not necessary if one tracks visited nodes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Once a node is visited, if it comes up in the heap again (having had a lower priority number associated with it earlier), it is popped-off and ignored.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Huffman coding requires one to repeatedly obtain the two lowest-frequency trees.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] A priority queue is one method of doing this.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Best-first search algorithms, like the A* search algorithm, find the shortest path between two vertices or nodes of a weighted graph, trying out the most promising routes first.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] A priority queue (also known as the *fringe*) is used to keep track of unexplored routes; the one for which the estimate (a lower bound in the case of A*) of the total path length is smallest is given highest priority.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] If memory limitations make best-first search impractical, variants like the SMA* algorithm can be used instead, with a double-ended priority queue to allow removal of low-priority items.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The Real-time Optimally Adapting Meshes (ROAM) algorithm computes a dynamically changing triangulation of a terrain.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] It works by splitting triangles where more detail is needed and merging them where less detail is needed.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The algorithm assigns each triangle in the terrain a priority, usually related to the error decrease if that triangle would be split.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The algorithm uses two priority queues, one for triangles that can be split and another for triangles that can be merged.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In each step the triangle from the split queue with the highest priority is split, or the triangle from the merge queue with the lowest priority is merged with its neighbours.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Using min heap priority queue in Prim's algorithm to find the minimum spanning tree of a connected and undirected graph, one can achieve a good running time.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] This min heap priority queue uses the min heap data structure which supports operations such as `insert`, `minimum`, `extract-min`, `decrease-key`.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In this implementation, the weight of the edges is used to decide the priority of the vertices.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Lower the weight, higher the priority and higher the weight, lower the priority.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Parallelization can be used to speed up priority queues, but requires some changes to the priority queue interface.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The reason for such changes is that a sequential update usually only has ${\textstyle O(1)}$ or ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost, and there is no practical gain to parallelize such an operation.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] One possible change is to allow the concurrent access of multiple processors to the same priority queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The second possible change is to allow batch operations that work on ${\textstyle k}$ elements, instead of just one element.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For example, `extractMin` will remove the first ${\textstyle k}$ elements with the highest priority.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] If the priority queue allows concurrent access, multiple processes can perform operations concurrently on that priority queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] First of all, the definition of the semantics of the individual operations is no longer obvious.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For example, if two processes want to extract the element with the highest priority, should they get the same element or different ones?
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] This restricts parallelism on the level of the program using the priority queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In addition, because multiple processes have access to the same element, this leads to contention.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The concurrent access to a priority queue can be implemented on a Concurrent Read, Concurrent Write (CRCW) PRAM model.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In the following the priority queue is implemented as a skip list.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In addition, an atomic synchronization primitive, CAS, is used to make the skip list lock-free.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The nodes of the skip list consists of a unique key, a priority, an array of pointers, for each level, to the next nodes and a `delete` mark.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The `delete` mark marks if the node is about to be deleted by a process.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] This ensures that other processes can react to the deletion appropriately.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] If the concurrent access to a priority queue is allowed, conflicts may arise between two processes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For example, a conflict arises if one process is trying to insert a new node, but at the same time another process is about to delete the predecessor of that node.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] There is a risk that the new node is added to the skip list, yet it is not longer reachable.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In this setting, operations on a priority queue is generalized to a batch of ${\textstyle k}$ elements.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For instance, `k_extract-min` deletes the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the priority queue and returns those.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In a shared-memory setting, the parallel priority queue can be easily implemented using parallel binary search trees and join-based tree algorithms.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] In particular, `k_extract-min` corresponds to a *split* on the binary search tree that has ${\textstyle O(\log n)}$ cost and yields a tree that contains the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] `k_insert` can be applied by a *union* of the original priority queue and the batch of insertions.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] If the batch is already sorted by the key, `k_insert` has ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}}))}$ cost.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Otherwise, we need to first sort the batch, so the cost will be ${\textstyle O(k\log(1+{\frac {n}{k}})+k\log k)=O(k\log n)}$ .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Other operations for priority queue can be applied similarly.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] For instance, `k_decrease-key` can be done by first applying `difference` and then `union`, which first deletes the elements and then inserts them back with the updated keys.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] All these operations are highly parallel, and the theoretical and practical efficiency can be found in related research papers.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The rest of this section discusses a queue-based algorithm on distributed memory.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] We assume each processor has its own local memory and a local (sequential) priority queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The elements of the global (parallel) priority queue are distributed across all processors.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] A `k_insert` operation assigns the elements uniformly random to the processors which insert the elements into their local queues.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Note that single elements can still be inserted into the queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Using this strategy the global smallest elements are in the union of the local smallest elements of every processor with high probability.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Thus each processor holds a representative part of the global priority queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] This property is used when `k_extract-min` is executed, as the smallest ${\textstyle m}$ elements of each local queue are removed and collected in a result set.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The elements in the result set are still associated with their original processor.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The number of elements ${\textstyle m}$ that is removed from each local queue depends on ${\textstyle k}$ and the number of processors ${\textstyle p}$ .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] By parallel selection the ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements of the result set are determined.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] With high probability these are the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] If not, ${\textstyle m}$ elements are again removed from each local queue and put into the result set.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] This is done until the global ${\textstyle k}$ smallest elements are in the result set.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Now these ${\textstyle k}$ elements can be returned.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] All other elements of the result set are inserted back into their local queues.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The running time of `k_extract-min` is expected ${\textstyle O({\frac {k}{p}}\log(n))}$ , where ${\textstyle k=\Omega (p\cdot \log(p))}$ and ${\textstyle n}$ is the size of the priority queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The priority queue can be further improved by not moving the remaining elements of the result set directly back into the local queues after a `k_extract-min` operation.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] This saves moving elements back and forth all the time between the result set and the local queues.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] By removing several elements at once a considerable speedup can be reached.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] But not all algorithms can use this kind of priority queue.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] Dijkstra's algorithm for example can not work on several nodes at once.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] The algorithm takes the node with the smallest distance from the priority queue and calculates new distances for all its neighbor nodes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] If you would take out ${\textstyle k}$ nodes, working at one node could change the distance of another one of the ${\textstyle k}$ nodes.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/priority-queue] So using k-element operations destroys the label setting property of Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] In graph theory, the **shortest path problem** is the problem of finding a path between two vertices (or nodes) in a graph such that the sum of the weights of its constituent edges is minimized.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The problem of finding the shortest path between two intersections on a road map may be modeled as a special case of the shortest path problem in graphs, where the vertices correspond to intersections and the edges correspond to road segments, each weighted by the length or distance of each segment.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The shortest path problem can be defined for graphs whether undirected, directed, or mixed.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The definition for undirected graphs states that every edge can be traversed in either direction.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Directed graphs require that consecutive vertices be connected by an appropriate directed edge.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Two vertices are adjacent when they are both incident to a common edge.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] A path in an undirected graph is a sequence of vertices $P=(v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{n})\in V\times V\times \cdots \times V$ such that $v_{i}$ is adjacent to $v_{i+1}$ for $1\leq i<n$ .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Such a path P is called a path of length $n-1$ from $v_{1}$ to $v_{n}$ .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] These generalizations have significantly more efficient algorithms than the simplistic approach of running a single-pair shortest path algorithm on all relevant pairs of vertices.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Several well-known algorithms exist for solving this problem and its variants.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Additional algorithms and associated evaluations may be found in Cherkassky, Goldberg & Radzik (1996).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] An algorithm using topological sorting can solve the single-source shortest path problem in time Θ(*E* + *V*) in arbitrarily-weighted directed acyclic graphs.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The following table is taken from Schrijver (2004), with some corrections and additions.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] A green background indicates an asymptotically best bound in the table; *L* is the maximum length (or weight) among all edges, assuming integer edge weights.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Finds a negative cycle or calculates distances to all vertices.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The all-pairs shortest path problem finds the shortest paths between every pair of vertices v, v' in the graph.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The all-pairs shortest paths problem for unweighted directed graphs was introduced by Shimbel (1953), who observed that it could be solved by a linear number of matrix multiplications that takes a total time of *O*(*V*4).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Shortest path algorithms are applied to automatically find directions between physical locations, such as driving directions on web mapping websites like MapQuest or Google Maps.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] For this application fast specialized algorithms are available.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] For example, if vertices represent the states of a puzzle like a Rubik's Cube and each directed edge corresponds to a single move or turn, shortest path algorithms can be used to find a solution that uses the minimum possible number of moves.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] In a networking or telecommunications mindset, this shortest path problem is sometimes called the min-delay path problem and usually tied with a widest path problem.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] For example, the algorithm may seek the shortest (min-delay) widest path, or widest shortest (min-delay) path.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] A more lighthearted application is the games of "six degrees of separation" that try to find the shortest path in graphs like movie stars appearing in the same film.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Other applications, often studied in operations research, include plant and facility layout, robotics, transportation, and VLSI design.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] A road network can be considered as a graph with positive weights.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The nodes represent road junctions and each edge of the graph is associated with a road segment between two junctions.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The weight of an edge may correspond to the length of the associated road segment, the time needed to traverse the segment, or the cost of traversing the segment.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Using directed edges it is also possible to model one-way streets.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Such graphs are special in the sense that some edges are more important than others for long-distance travel (e.g. highways).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] This property has been formalized using the notion of highway dimension.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] There are a great number of algorithms that exploit this property and are therefore able to compute the shortest path a lot quicker than would be possible on general graphs.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] All of these algorithms work in two phases.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] In the first phase, the graph is preprocessed without knowing the source or target node.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] In this phase, source and target node are known.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The idea is that the road network is static, so the preprocessing phase can be done once and used for a large number of queries on the same road network.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The algorithm with the fastest known query time is called hub labeling and is able to compute shortest path on the road networks of Europe or the US in a fraction of a microsecond.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] For shortest path problems in computational geometry, see Euclidean shortest path.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The shortest multiple disconnected path is a representation of the primitive path network within the framework of Reptation theory.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The widest path problem seeks a path so that the minimum label of any edge is as large as possible.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Other related problems may be classified into the following categories.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Unlike the shortest path problem, which can be solved in polynomial time in graphs without negative cycles, shortest path problems which include additional constraints on the desired solution path are called Constrained Shortest Path First, and are harder to solve.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] One example is the constrained shortest path problem, which attempts to minimize the total cost of the path while at the same time maintaining another metric below a given threshold.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] This makes the problem NP-complete (such problems are not believed to be efficiently solvable for large sets of data, see P = NP problem).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Another NP-complete example requires a specific set of vertices to be included in the path, which makes the problem similar to the Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The TSP is the problem of finding the shortest path that goes through every vertex exactly once, and returns to the start.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The problem of finding the longest path in a graph is also NP-complete.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The Canadian traveller problem and the stochastic shortest path problem are generalizations where either the graph is not completely known to the mover, changes over time, or where actions (traversals) are probabilistic.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Sometimes, the edges in a graph have personalities: each edge has its own selfish interest.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] An example is a communication network, in which each edge is a computer that possibly belongs to a different person.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Different computers have different transmission speeds, so every edge in the network has a numeric weight equal to the number of milliseconds it takes to transmit a message.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Our goal is to send a message between two points in the network in the shortest time possible.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] If we know the transmission-time of each computer (the weight of each edge), then we can use a standard shortest-paths algorithm.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] If we do not know the transmission times, then we have to ask each computer to tell us its transmission-time.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] But, the computers may be selfish: a computer might tell us that its transmission time is very long, so that we will not bother it with our messages.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] A possible solution to this problem is to use a variant of the VCG mechanism, which gives the computers an incentive to reveal their true weights.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] In some cases, the main goal is not to find the shortest path, but only to detect if the graph contains a negative cycle.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Many problems can be framed as a form of the shortest path for some suitably substituted notions of addition along a path and taking the minimum.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The general approach to these is to consider the two operations to be those of a semiring.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Semiring multiplication is done along the path, and the addition is between paths.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] This general framework is known as the algebraic path problem.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] Most of the classic shortest-path algorithms (and new ones) can be formulated as solving linear systems over such algebraic structures.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] More recently, an even more general framework for solving these (and much less obviously related problems) has been developed under the banner of valuation algebras.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] In real-life, a transportation network is usually stochastic and time-dependent.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The travel duration on a road segment depends on many factors such as the amount of traffic (origin-destination matrix), road work, weather, accidents and vehicle breakdowns.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] A more realistic model of such a road network is a stochastic time-dependent (STD) network.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] There is no accepted definition of optimal path under uncertainty (that is, in stochastic road networks).
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] It is a controversial subject, despite considerable progress during the past decade.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] One common definition is a path with the minimum expected travel time.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The main advantage of this approach is that it can make use of efficient shortest path algorithms for deterministic networks.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] However, the resulting optimal path may not be reliable, because this approach fails to address travel time variability.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] To tackle this issue, some researchers use travel duration distribution instead of its expected value.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] So, they find the probability distribution of total travel duration using different optimization methods such as dynamic programming and Dijkstra's algorithm .
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] These methods use stochastic optimization, specifically stochastic dynamic programming to find the shortest path in networks with probabilistic arc length.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The terms *travel time reliability* and *travel time variability* are used as opposites in the transportation research literature: the higher the variability, the lower the reliability of predictions.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] To account for variability, researchers have suggested two alternative definitions for an optimal path under uncertainty.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] The *most reliable path* is one that maximizes the probability of arriving on time given a travel time budget.
[src:dijkstra-shortest-path/shortest-path-problem] An *α-reliable path* is one that minimizes the travel time budget required to arrive on time with a given probability.
